    <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
      <head>Biographical History</head>
      <p>Gregory Corso (1929â€“2001) was an American poet, the youngest of 
a group popularly known as the "Beat Generation" writers, in company with Jack Kerouac, Allen Ginsberg, 
and William Burroughs.</p><p>Corso was also the first of the group to be published ("The Vestal Lady on 
Brattle" and other poems, in 1952).  Writer Ted Morgan said of them, "If Ginsberg, Kerouac, and Burroughs 
were the Three Musketeers of the movement, Corso was their D'Artagnan."</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
      <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
      <p>The 
        
        
        
        <emph render="bold">Gregory Corso Collection</emph> consists of two items of outgoing correspondence, the manuscript for Corso's book 
        
        
        
        <emph render="italic">Long Live Man</emph>, and a notebook containing poems and miscellaneous notes.</p>
    </scopecontent>
